<HEADLINE>
FT  20 AUG 93 / Roof support system at Bilsthorpe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE ROOF support system used at Bilsthorpe
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
and deep mines throughout the world - relies on steel bolts three metres
long which are coated with adhesive resin and rammed into the rock above the
coal, Clive Cookson writes.
The bolts strengthen the sandstone rock in the same way as steel can
reinforce concrete. Mr John Harrison, lecturer in rock mechanics at the
Royal School of Mines, London, said it was a common misunderstanding that
bolts were used to attach a roof to a hard rock stratum. 'In fact the rock
supports itself and the tunnel roof becomes a strong beam.'
The photograph shows a rock bolted roof at Asfordby pit, Leicestershire. The
steel mesh hung from the bolts does not give structural strength but is
intended to prevent small pieces of coal or rock falling.
Mr Harrison said yesterday that - contrary to claims by the National Union
of Mineworkers - rock bolting was faster and cheaper than traditional steel
arches and also a safer way to support the roof.
He said: 'Rock engineers understand that if you make the rock capable of
supporting itself, it is far stronger than any engineering material. Steel
arches allow the rock to fail around the arch.'
</TEXT>
