<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 93 / Singapore presidential race off to a slow start
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SINGAPORE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SINGAPORE yesterday formally accepted two nominees for the country's first
direct presidential election, but with no rallies or opposition candidates
in sight, the race promises little in the way of spectacle, Reuter reports
from Singapore.
A government commission announced it had accepted the candidacies of Mr Ong
Teng Cheong, who resigned as deputy prime minister to run for president, and
Mr Chua Kim Yeow, a former senior government official.
Mr Tan Soo Phuan and Mr Joshua Jeyaretnam were the only opposition figures
seeking to run. Both were declared ineligible under a law which, in effect,
rules out all but senior members of Singapore's establishment.
'It is anti-democratic,' shouted Mr Tan after police escorted him from the
nomination centre yesterday.
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong said on Sunday only about 400 people were
eligible as candidates under the law.
Political analysts say few Singaporeans doubt that Mr Ong will win the
contest with the support of the ruling People's Action party, which has been
in power since independence in 1965.
</TEXT>
