<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 93 / International Company News: Nedlloyd suffers mid-term
deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEPRESSED freight rates pushed Nedlloyd, the Dutch shipping and road haulage
group, into a Fl 116m (Dollars 60m) net loss for the 1993 first half from a
slim profit of Fl 1m a year earlier.
The company, which described the result as 'most unsatisfactory', said
results in the second half were expected to show clear improvement, though
the figure would remain negative.
In a breakdown of developments over the first six months, Nedlloyd said a
'low point' was reached in the first quarter when losses totalled Fl 86m.
This was followed by a narrowing of losses to Fl 30m in the second quarter.
The ocean-shipping division swung into an operating loss of Fl 62m in the
first half from a Fl 34m profit a year earlier. Although land-based
transport and distribution remained profitable, operating results fell to Fl
5m from Fl 8m.
The company said it was not clear whether road haulage second-half results
would match those in the same period of 1992 because of continuing recession
in Europe.
</TEXT>
