<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Once again there is an abundance of sport and from 11 in the morning until 8
at night BBC2 is devoted to it pretty well exclusively. Athletics And
Cricket brings live coverage from the World Athletics Championships in
Stuttgart and the sixth Test (or 'Walkover') which begins today at the Oval.
Christopher Hitchens, described as 'cultural critic at large for Vanity
Fair' is one of those people who tend to be described as 'clever', a word
used by the chattering classes to mean pretentious, showy but shallow, or
supercilious. In Witness (9.00 C4) he reports on the leaders of some of the
bizarre cults in Los Angeles.
The questionable thesis in Episode 1 of Pandora's Box blinded me to the
strength of the other programmes when the series was first shown. The repeat
screening (9.30 BBC2) moves on to the story of 'the men on whom Dr
Strangelove was based ..who believed the world could be controlled by the
scientific manipulation of fear'.
BBC Proms Live features the American trumpeter Wynton Marsalis with his jazz
septet (10.05 BBC1 and Radio 3).
