<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 93 / Currencies 'face more turmoil'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPE could be facing more currency turmoil in spite of the decision to
widen the fluctuation margins of the European exchange rate mechanism to 15
per cent, the National Institute of Economic and Social Research warned
yesterday.
In its quarterly report the economic research body said the failure of the
ERM demonstrated the weakness of market intervention as a means of defending
exchange-rate bands.
Moving to a system of wider bands or even free-floating 'does not put the
monetary authorities back in control', it said.
Mr Wynne Godley, professor of applied economics at Cambridge University and
one of the Treasury's seven-strong panel of independent economic
forecasters, today warns that market forces alone are insufficient to save
the European Community from 'endemic recession'.
Writing in today's London Review of Books, he says there is a pressing need
for 'some supranational authority, call it a federal government' to pursue
macro-economic policies.
Letters, Page 14
