<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 93 / Review of bus industry demanded
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FULL review of the bus industry was called for yesterday by the Monopolies
and Mergers Commission after it found another local bus company guilty of
anti-competitive behaviour designed to force a competitor out of the market.
There have been a number of instances of bus companies attempting to squeeze
rivals out of the market since deregulation. Most recently, in June the
commission found Southdown Motor Services guilty of trying to force a rival
off routes in Bognor Regis, West Sussex, by pitching fares at an uneconomic
level.
Responding to the commission's report on bus services in mid and west Kent,
Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs minister, said the government was not
yet convinced of the need for a wide-scale review.
But he said it would consider the commission's suggestions for tightening
the application of competition law to the bus industry.
The commission said the introduction by Maidstone &amp; District Motor Services
of additional bus services timed immediately before those of a competitor
was designed to force the competitor's withdrawal from the routes.
This behaviour, together with the use of selective fare reductions on
journeys immediately in front of a competitor's and other actions were
practices which operated, or were likely to operate, against the public
interest, the commission said.
The commission also examined M&amp;D's operation of the Chatham bus station and
found the terms on which it offered access to other bus companies
unreasonable, denying passengers a choice of services from the station.
Mr Hamilton said he had asked the director-general of fair trading to seek
undertakings within three months from M&amp;D that it would address the
commission's complaints.
</TEXT>
