<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 93 / Gas companies reject price fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RIVAL GAS companies yesterday attacked claims by British Gas that the
introduction of competition to the household supply market would mean higher
prices for large groups of customers.
'These statements are not true, but British Gas is scoring some good points
with them,' said Mr Peter Bryant, deputy chairman of Utilicorp UK, which has
linked up with six regional electricity companies in order to enter the
domestic supply market.
The Monopolies and Mergers Commission recommended on Tuesday in two reports
on the gas industry that household customers be given a free choice of
supplier by 2002.
It also quoted in its reports figures by British Gas showing that prices for
1.4m of its customers using small amounts of gas would double in a free
market. A further 60 per cent of the company's 18m consumers could be worse
off.
The commission said that although prices could go up in the shorter term,
the introduction of competition would bring the prospect of price reduction
in the long run.
Mr Cedric Brown, chief executive of British Gas, denied allegations of
scaremongering. 'We've said all along the removal of the monopoly should
only take place after the government has given careful consideration to all
these issues,' he said.
Competitors disagree with claims that they will only be looking to
cherry-pick in a competitive market and supply the most profitable
customers.
Rival suppliers say they are already delivering gas to some high-volume
domestic customers who have seen savings of between 10 per cent and 12 per
cent.
Competitors are also annoyed at claims that prices will rise in a more
competitive market. They believe it could deter the government from opening
up household supplies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Gas.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4923 Gas Transmission and Distribution.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
