<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 93 / Pit probe will focus on roof supports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COAL was expected to launch an inquiry today into the Bilsthorpe pit
accident, in which at least one miner died, with attention focused on the
mine's roof support, Michael Smith writes.
The roof bolting system on which the trapped miners were working at the
Nottinghamshire pit has been introduced gradually throughout British Coal
mines over the past decade in the face of strong opposition from the
National Union of Mineworkers.
British Coal said yesterday that roof bolting was more scientific and safer
than traditional methods.
The accident inquiry will involve British Coal, the mining inspectorate and
the mining unions.
Yesterday's accident happened on a section of mine where roof bolting is
being applied. British Coal said yesterday that the circumstances
surrounding the accident were unclear.
Roof bolting works in a similar way to a screw being driven into a wall
through a plug. A hole is driven into the roof. It is then packed with a
glue-type resin and a bolt is inserted. Roof bolts are placed about a metre
apart.
British Coal said virtually all its remaining mines used roof bolting,
although the system was not suitable for all parts of mines. Before roof
bolting, pit tunnels were held up with a system of steel arches and girders.
Mr Arthur Scargill, NUM president, said yesterday that he was totally
against roof bolting as a primary support and had been campaigning against
it for many years.
</TEXT>
