<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 93 / Slide in pay rises 'bottoms out'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FALL in pay rises appears to be bottoming out after hitting the lowest
levels since its surveys began in 1976, the Reward Group of independent pay
analysts said yesterday.
Mr Steve Flather, managing director of Reward, said: 'There is evidence that
we have reached the bottom for all main groups of employees.'
The latest survey finds the settlement level for clerical and manual workers
running at between 2.3 per cent and 2.5 per cent. However, taking into
account 'pay drift', mainly seniority increments and performance pay,
earnings increases for clerical workers were as high as 5.3 per cent in the
12 months to June 1993. In July the figure fell to 3.9 per cent. For a
director's secretary over the past year it was 5.5 per cent; 3.1 per cent
for a receptionist; 2.1 per cent for a clerk typist; and 5.8 per cent for
manual and skilled crafts workers.
The Reward Group, Reward House, Diamond Way, Stone Business Park, Stone,
Staffordshire, ST15 0SD. Pounds 160.
</TEXT>
