<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 93 / EC steel shake-up 'overdue'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LORDS EC energy, industry and transport committee today rejects any
notion of 'national burden-sharing' in planned cuts to Europe's steelmaking
capacity.
In a strongly worded report the committee says large-scale restructuring of
the EC steel sector, which is suffering from chronic overcapacity and
recession, is long overdue.
It warns against state subsidies to support inefficient production and says:
'There is a real danger that efficient private firms such as British Steel .
. . will suffer at the expense of inefficient state firms such as the
bankrupt Ilva in Italy.'
Mr Brian Moffat, chairman of British Steel, has argued that continental
steelmakers should reduce overcapacity to match the heavy cuts made in the
UK.
The committee's report comes at a sensitive time for the EC steel industry.
More than 30m tonnes of crude steel capacity have been recommended for
closure, leading to an estimated 70,000 job cuts.
The committee says British Steel does not expect to participate in the
current closures but the UK government has not ruled out further cuts.
It says competitive forces should be allowed to determine the future
structure and location of the industry, but expresses concern about the
human costs of closures.
Restructuring the EC Steel Industry. House of Lords Select Committee on the
European Communities. HMSO. Pounds 18.
</TEXT>
