<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 93 / Norway in talks to prevent US sanctions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NORWAY will be holding a series of talks with US government officials
through September in an effort to avoid US trade sanctions, writes Karen
Fossli in Oslo.
Mr Ron Brown, US secretary of commerce, this month made an official
recommendation that Norway's decision to resume hunting minke whales in
defiance of the International Whaling Commission moratorium undermined the
effectiveness of the IWC's conservation regime.
Under a provision of US fishing law, the Pelly amendment, such a step gives
President Bill Clinton the authority to impose trade sanctions against the
offending country. Sanctions could be aimed at US imports of Norwegian
fishery products, valued at between Dollars 50 and Dollars 100m (Pounds
67.1m) a year.
Norway's whalers ended their hunt last month, falling four short of a
government-set quota of 160 minke whales. In autumn they will resume for
scientific purposes.
