<HEADLINE>
FT  19 AUG 93 / Japan shies away from interest rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of Japan has no plans to cut the official discount rate, despite
the yen's sharp rise against the dollar, Mr Yasushi Mieno, the Bank's
governor, said yesterday.
'The mechanism for economic recovery is in place,' Mr Mieno said. The Bank
did not consider that the Japanese economy had hit bottom yet, Mr Mieno
said, but neither did it see any grounds to change its view that the economy
would pick up in the latter half of the fiscal year.
While consumer spending and private capital investment remained sluggish,
recent progress in stock adjustment and past fiscal and monetary measures
were providing the fundamental conditions for recovery, he said.
Mr Mieno's remarks came amid widespread expectations of an easing of
monetary policy to stimulate Japan's still weak domestic economy and help
curb the recent sharp rise of the yen.
The currency's movement has been largely attributed to speculation on the
markets that the US sees a higher yen as a means of reducing Japan's trade
surplus.
The yen took a breather on the markets yesterday, trading in a narrow range
between Y101.32 and Y101.70 against the dollar, as market traders waited for
further developments to give them direction.
Its future movements will depend largely on what, if any, specific measures
the Japanese government comes up with today, at the emergency meeting of
ministers, to address the country's high surplus.
Businesses and economists alike have been calling for a substantial
reduction in the discount rate to provide a psychological boost to
corporations, help stimluate the domestic economy and send a clear sign to
the currency markets that Japan is serious about tackling its huge trade
surplus.
Although Mr Mieno expressed strong displeasure with the current speed of the
yen's rise, which was 'excessive' and would have an adverse effect on
Japan's economy, the best way to tackle the surplus was to get the economy
back on the road to growth by taking dramatic steps to open and deregulate
Japan's markets, he said.
Deregulation, which is an issue the coalition government is keen to address,
was important not just to help imports enter the country but to increase
investment in Japan, he said.
</TEXT>
