<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Government Bonds: Better-than-expected PSBR boosts
long-dated gilts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE COMBINATION of better-than-expected borrowing figures and general
enthusiasm over the inflation outlook helped to boost long-dated UK
government bonds by three-quarters of a point yesterday.
Short-dated gilts were little changed as the market's attention shifted from
hopes of an imminent cut in the base rate to the good inflation background
and yesterday's release of the July public sector borrowing requirement
figure.
The PSBR figure of Pounds 1.5bn was below market expectations of Pounds
1.8bn to Pounds 1.9bn, helped by proceeds from the sale of the third tranche
of shares in British Telecommunications.
Economists pointed out that the latest Confederation of British Industry
survey, published yesterday, indicated economic recovery without the threat
of a pick-up in inflation, a scenario which was warmly welcomed by the gilt
market.
The Liffe gilt futures contract opened at 113.01 and reached a high of
113.24 before slipping to 113.21 by late afternoon. With the rally
concentrated on longer-dated stocks, the gilt yield curve flattened.
FRENCH government bonds ended lower on the day, despite the Banque de
France's half-point cut in the overnight rate to 8.75 per cent yesterday
morning. While the franc strengthened on the news, the bond market sold off
as both domestic and international investors took profits.
Elsewhere in Europe, the German bond market closed higher on the day, more
than making up for early weakness. The Liffe bund futures contract opened at
97.15, and rose to a high of 97.37 before ending at around 97.35.
MR JOHN Dawkins, the Australian Treasurer, forecast higher-than-expected
inflation in his budget speech yesterday, which had a negative impact on
government bonds.
He said the consumer price index (CPI) was expected to rise by 3.5 per cent
in the fiscal year 1993-94. The market had expected a CPI rise of between
2.5 per cent and 3.0 per cent.
Bond prices fell on the news, with the yield on the 9.5 per cent bond due
2003 rising to 6.87 per cent, from 6.80 per cent just before the budget
speech.
The Australian government projected a budget deficit of ADollars 16bn for
the year ending June 30 1994, widening from a revised deficit of ADollars
14.6bn in the 1992 - 93 fiscal year.
JAPANESE bonds saw volatile trading, taking their cue from the yen, but
ended little changed on the day. The yen strengthened to a post-war high of
Y100.25 to the US dollar, before slipping back.
The yield on the benchmark No 145 issue opened at 4.065 per cent and traded
in a range of 4.03 to 4.11 per cent before ending at 4.07 per cent.
In the futures market, the December contract reached a high of 111.22 and
ended Tokyo trading little changed at 110.90, but slipped back in London to
110.72.
AFTER early gains, longer-dated US Treasury prices fell back on
disappointment that the Federal Reserve did not add reserves to the system.
In late trading the benchmark 30-year government bond was down  3/32 at 99
1/4 , yielding 6.304 per cent. At the short end, the two-year note was down
 1/16 at 100 15/32 , to yield 3.980 per cent.
The market lacked a firm direction in morning trading, but longer-dated
securities maintained their upward momentum. The gains sent yields on the
30-year bond to record lows. Traders said the strength was primarily due to
buying in anticipation of a coupon pass by the Fed, which would involve the
central bank buying Treasury coupons outright.
In the afternoon long prices fell back when a coupon pass failed to
materialise. The losses, however, were minimal, and trading remained light
throughout the session.
</TEXT>
