<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Californian insurer loses battle over rebates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALLSTATE Insurance yesterday became the biggest insurer to concede defeat in
the battle with Californian regulators over Proposition 103, the
controversial state legislation which decided that premiums on motor and
other types of property/casualty insurance should be rolled back, and
rebates made.
Allstate and the California Department of Insurance said the company had
agreed to repay Dollars 110m in rebates to 2.9m policyholders who held
policies in the year to November 1989. This represents 5.3 per cent of the
company's written premiums during the period.
The agreement marks the biggest single victory for Mr John Garamendi, the
politically-ambitious Californian insurance commissioner, in his battle with
insurance companies over rebates under Proposition 103, which was passed in
1988 on a 'voter initiative'. It takes to 7m the number of people who will
have received rebates.
Allstate, which had been one of the most vociferous opponents of the
legislation, said it had decided to settle to put the dispute behind it. The
cost of the settlement, which had been provided for in previous years, would
not affect 1993 earnings. The company will pay rebates averaging Dollars 66
on each auto policy, Dollars 26 per homeowners policy, and Dollars 207 on
each commercial policy.
Mr Garamendi, while welcoming the settlement, said: 'This agreement should
send a signal (to other insurers) that either through the courts or directly
with companies, we will see to it that rebates are paid.'
</TEXT>
