<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Merseyside postal workers mobilise for strike ballot
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S postal service faces the possibility of further disruption in
spite of yesterday's settlement of a two-week dispute by Royal Mail staff in
Cardiff.
A strike ballot of 1,100 postal workers on Merseyside is being prepared to
protest against a threat by local management to reduce full-time delivery
jobs as part of a plan to cut costs by 5 per cent.
The Union of Communication Workers fears the loss of a quarter of the
full-time jobs at Merseyside's 32 postal delivery offices if the Royal Mail
introduces part-time staff to make second deliveries.
The ballot is the latest sign of unrest among staff as the Royal Mail
presses ahead with its quality of service scheme designed to increase
efficiency in the face of rising competition.
In Cardiff, in a ballot organised by the UCW, the staff voted by 556 to 154
to end their industrial action. More than 1m letters were held up by the
strike and the Royal Mail warned it may take a week to clear the backlog.
The Royal Mail said last night it was 'premature' to discuss the plan for
Merseyside, although consultations were going on with the UCW. However, Mr
John Ireland, a local UCW official, warned: 'If talks fail we will go for a
strike ballot.'
An internal Royal Mail management document obtained by the union reveals
details of the Liverpool 'delivery plan' which are to be discussed in staff
briefings this month for implementation in September.
The document says Liverpool has low levels of productivity and jobs can be
safeguarded only by raising productivity.
The plan aims to align working hours and the number of workers more closely
and calls for early starts to ensure the maximum amount of mail is delivered
on time on first delivery.
At present, it says, 85 per cent of the postal traffic is available for
first delivery and this workload is handled by 60 per cent of the delivery
hours. The remaining 15 per cent of the workload is taken out on a second
delivery that uses 40 per cent of the working hours available.
