<HEADLINE>
FT  18 AUG 93 / Merseyside postal workers to vote on part-time plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FURTHER disruption is threatening Britain's postal services in spite of
yesterday's settlement of the two-week dispute by Royal Mail staff in
Cardiff.
A strike ballot of 1,100 postal workers on Merseyside is being prepared in
protest at a threat by local management to reduce full-time delivery jobs as
part of a plan to cut costs by 5 per cent.
The Union of Communication Workers fears the loss of a quarter of the
full-time jobs at Merseyside's 32 postal delivery offices if the Royal Mail
introduces part-time staff to make second deliveries.
The ballot is the latest sign of unrest among staff as the Royal Mail
presses ahead with its quality of service scheme designed to increase
efficiency in the face of rising competition.
In Cardiff, in an individual ballot organised by the UCW, the staff voted by
556 to 154 to end their industrial action. More than 1m letters were held up
by the strike and the Royal Mail warned it may take a week to return the
postal services to normal.
The Royal Mail said last night it was 'premature' to discuss the plan for
Merseyside, although consultations were going on with the UCW. However, Mr
John Ireland, a local UCW official warned: 'If talks fail we will go for a
strike ballot.'
An internal Royal Mail management document obtained by the union reveals
details of the Liverpool 'delivery plan' which are to be discussed in staff
briefings this month for implementation in September. 'At the moment the
union are trying to block proposals,' it complains and calls for
'verbal/face-to-face communication' with the staff.
The document warns jobs can be safeguarded only by raising productivity in
deliveries. It points out: 'It is an established fact that our competitors
such as Securicor, UNT, DHL and other private operators have found ways
round our legal monopoly.'
'This competition has grown by 50 per cent in the last two years and this in
a time of recession,' says the document. 'It is estimated that we presently
have 95 per cent of the letter delivery market but if competition continues
to grow at the present rate this share will fall to 60 per cent in the next
five years.' It adds: 'For these reasons we have been targeted to make
productivity savings.'
The paper goes on: 'In addition Liverpool has low levels of productivity
when compared with other areas. Therefore changes must and will happen and
staff owe it to themselves to at least listen to what is being proposed.'
The Royal Mail plan aims to align working hours and the number of workers
more closely to the workload on Merseyside.
At present, it says, 85 per cent of the postal traffic is available for
first delivery and this workload is handled by 60 per cent of the delivery
hours. The remaining 15 per cent of the workload is taken out on a second
delivery that uses 40 per cent of the working hours available.
'Clearly the areas for productivity gains are on second delivery,' the
document says. It calls for early starts to ensure the maximum amount of
mail is delivered on time on first delivery.
</TEXT>
